\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Observability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A system is 
\series bold
observable
\series default
 if its state can be reconstructed from output measurements over time.
 This property ensures that unmeasured states can be inferred using a mathematic
al model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Observability Condition for Linear Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a linear time-invariant (LTI) system: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{x} & =Ax+Bu,\\
y & =Cx+Du,
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the state vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the input, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is the measured output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system is 
\series bold
observable
\series default
 if the 
\shape italic
observability matrix
\shape default
 has full rank: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}=\begin{bmatrix}C\\
CA\\
CA^{2}\\
\vdots\\
CA^{n-1}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{rank}(\mathcal{O})=n$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of states), then all states can be estimated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Observability for Nonlinear Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For nonlinear systems, observability is analyzed using the 
\shape italic
Observability Gramian
\shape default
 or by applying Lie derivatives.
 The system dynamics are given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{x} & =f(x,u),\\
y & =h(x,u).
\end{align}

\end_inset

The nonlinear observability rank condition requires computing the Lie derivative
s of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x,u)$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,u)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Observer Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a system is observable, an 
\shape italic
observer
\shape default
 (state estimator) can be designed to reconstruct non-measured states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Luenberger Observer (Linear Systems)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an observable LTI system, a Luenberger observer estimates the state:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\hat{x}}=A\hat{x}+Bu+L(y-C\hat{x}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated state, and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the observer gain.
 The gain 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is designed such that the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $(A-LC)$
\end_inset

 are stable (negative real parts).
\end_layout

